{"id":"1512.07286","submitter":"James Yorke","authors":"Suddhasattwa Das and Chris B. Dock and Yoshitaka Saiki and Martin\n  Salgado-Flores and Evelyn Sander and Jin Wu and James A. Yorke","title":"Measuring quasiperiodicity","comments":"5 figures","journal-ref":"Europhysics letters, 116(4), 2016","doi":"10.1209/0295-5075/114/40005","report-no":null,"categories":"math-ph math.MP nlin.CD","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The Birkhoff Ergodic Theorem asserts under mild conditions that Birkhoff\naverages (i.e. time averages computed along a trajectory) converge to the space\naverage. For sufficiently smooth systems, our small modification of numerical\nBirkhoff averages significantly speeds the convergence rate for quasiperiodic\ntrajectories -- by a factor of $10^{25}$ for 30-digit precision arithmetic,\nmaking it a useful computational tool for autonomous dynamical systems. Many\ndynamical systems and especially Hamiltonian systems are a complex mix of\nchaotic and quasiperiodic behaviors, and chaotic trajectories near\nquasiperiodic points can have long near-quasiperiodic transients. Our method\ncan help determine which initial points are in a quasiperiodic set and which\nare chaotic. We use our {\\bf weighted Birkhoff average} to study quasiperiodic\nsystems, to distinguishing between chaos and quasiperiodicity, and for\ncomputing rotation numbers for self-intersecting curves in the plane.\nFurthermore we introduce the Embedding Continuation Method which is a\nsignificantly simpler, general method for computing rotation numbers.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 22 Dec 2015 22:34:12 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 26 Feb 2016 18:33:45 GMT"}],"update_date":"2018-01-31"}
