{"id":"1512.07514","submitter":"Saeid  Alikhani","authors":"Saeid Alikhani, Davood Fatehi and Sandi Klav\\v{z}ar","title":"On the structure of dominating graphs","comments":"8 pages, 1 figure","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.CO","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The $k$-dominating graph $D_k(G)$ of a graph $G$ is defined on the vertex set\nconsisting of dominating sets of $G$ with cardinality at most $k$, two such\nsets being adjacent if they differ by either adding or deleting a single\nvertex. A graph is a dominating graph if it is isomorphic to $D_k(G)$ for some\ngraph $G$ and some positive integer $k$. Answering a question of Haas and\nSeyffarth for graphs without isolates, it is proved that if $G$ is such a graph\nof order $n\\ge 2$ and with $G\\cong D_k(G)$, then $k=2$ and $G=K_{1,n-1}$ for\nsome $n\\ge 4$. It is also proved that for a given $r$ there exist only a finite\nnumber of $r$-regular, connected dominating graphs of connected graphs. In\nparticular, $C_6$ and $C_8$ are the only dominating graphs in the class of\ncycles. Some results on the order of dominating graphs are also obtained.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 23 Dec 2015 15:24:41 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Sun, 24 Apr 2016 08:52:22 GMT"}],"update_date":"2016-04-26"}
